Use **plain domain functions grouped by use-case/module**, with thin route handlers as orchestrators.  
For your codebase, that is the best-fit default over new service classes.

- Your own solved pattern explicitly says this: “follow existing module export pattern (functions, not classes)” in [god-handler extraction doc](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/docs/solutions/logic-errors/god-handler-extraction-requires-domain-function-pattern.md).
- You already have a good example of thin route + extracted handler in [confirm route](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/apps/tma/src/app/api/user/[userId]/swaps/confirm/route.ts), while a “god handler” still exists in [decline route](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/apps/tma/src/app/api/user/[userId]/swaps/decline/route.ts).
- Your feed module is already function-first and reusable ([session domain functions](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/packages/core/src/lib/backend/feeds/session.ts)).
- Wrapper stack is already designed for orchestration (`createRouteHandler` + middleware + response helpers): [routeHandler](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/packages/core/src/lib/api/routeHandler.ts), [responseHelpers](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/packages/core/src/lib/api/responseHelpers.ts).

Recommended pattern:

1. Route file: auth/params/body parse, call use-case function(s), map errors to response.
2. Domain use-case function(s): business rules, DB/Redis writes, transactional boundaries.
3. Shared infra helpers: notification, cache invalidation, serialization, analytics side effects.

Use classes only when you truly need instance state/configurable dependencies. In this repo, most “services” are effectively stateless, so classes add ceremony without much value.

Suggested extraction shape (text-only):

```ts
// route.ts
const POST = createRouteHandler({
  POST: withSubscriptionValidation(async (req, ctx, auth) => {
    const input = await parseAndValidate(req, ctx, auth);
    const result = await declineSwapUseCase(input);
    return jsonResponse(req, result);
  }),
}).POST!;
```

```ts
// domain/swaps/declineSwap.ts
export async function declineSwapUseCase(input: DeclineSwapInput): Promise<DeclineSwapResult> {
  // validate business preconditions
  // prisma transaction
  // call shared domain helpers (book mutation, notifications, cache invalidation)
  // return domain result DTO
}
```

If you want, I can draft a concrete extraction blueprint for one specific 300+ line route (`decline`, `batch`, or `notify/deliver`) with function boundaries and exact responsibilities.

